# Sentinel Table Standard

Every data table in this app — existing or new — must follow this pattern.
Do not invent a new table pattern. Reuse the existing shared components.

## Required for every table

1. **Filters** live in a distinct bordered "Filters" section above the
   table, using the shared filter bar component — never a page-specific
   one-off filter UI.
2. **Every real column gets a filter**, classified by its actual data
   type:
   - Low-cardinality (status, type, category) → checkbox/dropdown of
     real distinct values
   - Numeric (%, scores, counts) → min/max range
   - Boolean / has-doesn't-have → simple toggle
   - Free-text / near-unique (names, titles, notes, IDs) → contains
     text search
   - Person/owner/assignee fields → TEXT INPUT matching live User data.
     NEVER a dropdown of cached/hardcoded names — this has caused real
     bugs before.
3. **Manage Filters button**: all filters individually toggleable,
   default to 5-6 most useful visible, rest hidden. Persist per user
   (Clerk ID), survive logout, via the existing UserTablePreference
   mechanism — never a new preferences system.
4. **Manage Columns button**: same persistence mechanism as Manage
   Filters. The row-identifier column and any actions column can never
   be hidden.
5. **Search inside Manage Filters and Manage Columns**: once a page has
   more than ~8 filters or columns available, both the Manage Filters
   and Manage Columns panels must include a small search input at the
   top to filter the option list — don't make the user scroll a long
   unsearchable list.
6. **Sorting — two mechanisms, both required** (this supersedes any
   earlier guidance that said "no separate sort control" — a sort
   button beside Manage Columns is now required in addition to
   per-header sorting):
   - Click any column header to sort by it, with a direction indicator
     (arrow) shown on the header. State stored in the URL (?sort=&dir=).
   - A separate sort-summary button sits beside the Manage Columns
     button (e.g. "Release ID (A→Z)"), showing the current sort at a
     glance and offering quick preset options. This is in addition to
     per-header click-sort, not a replacement for it.
7. **Sticky table header** while scrolling vertically — always visible.
8. **Sticky first column** (row identifier) while scrolling
   horizontally, on wide tables.
9. **Both scrollbars visible and styled** — horizontal AND vertical,
   whichever axes actually overflow. Never hide the native scrollbar.
   Add an edge-fade cue when more columns exist off-screen. Confirm
   legible in both light and dark mode.
10. **Row styling**: separate rows with a horizontal divider line only.
    Do NOT add vertical divider lines between columns — no grid/cell-
    border look. On row hover, apply a smooth transition (background
    and/or border highlight fades in, not an instant snap) so hovering
    down a list feels fluid.
11. **All filtering is server-side** (Prisma `where` clauses). Never
    filter by fetching everything and narrowing client-side.
12. **Mobile**: horizontal scroll + sticky first column is the default
    mobile pattern (not a card rebuild), per the approved responsive
    plan. Only Env Booking-tier extreme-width tables get a card/summary
    fallback — ask before adding a new one.
13. **Page description + Know more** (one-time product requirement —
    not a reason to invent a second docs system): every table page
    header uses the shared `TopBar` with `pageKey` so a real ~2-line
    `summary` from `lib/page-documentation.ts` appears under the title,
    plus a "Know more" link that opens the **same** `PageDocumentation`
    popup already wired to that page's Help button (via
    `requestPageDocumentationOpen`). Do not build a duplicate modal or
    hand-roll per-page description markup.

## Before touching any SHARED component (filter bar, DataTable, column
picker, sort button, etc.)

Any change must be scoped via a new prop/config that only the calling
page opts into. NEVER change a shared component's default behavior —
this has caused real cross-page regressions before (Calendar once
inherited Releases' entire filter set this way). If a change might
affect more than one page, audit every consumer of that component
first and report back before changing it.

## When building a genuinely NEW table/page

Audit real columns from the actual schema/data first — do not guess or
copy another page's filter/column list. Classify each column per the
rules above, then build.
